description: Japan's parliamentary elections reveal a weakened Liberal Democratic Party. Diminished by its slush fund scandal and difficulties in taming the country's inflation, Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba's LDP is likely to embark on a search for new partners for a possible coalition.
title: In Japan, the ruling party is about to lose the majority it has held since 2012

description: Earlier on Sunday, Israeli Defense Minister Yoav Gallant said 'painful concessions' would be needed in negotiations and that military action alone would not achieve the country's war aims. Out of 251 hostages seized by Palestinian militants during the October 7 attack, 97 are still held in Gaza including 34 the Israeli military says are dead.
title: Egypt proposes two-day Gaza truce in hope of 'a complete ceasefire'

description: On a visit to Rabat starting on Monday, Emmanuel Macron will solemnize the reconciliation with Morocco after a three-year feud, at the cost of a new crisis with Algiers.
title: Algeria casts a shadow over the French-Moroccan reunion

description: Columnist Alain Frachon analyses the mystery of the trust Trump's voters place in him, despite the former president's radical and and increasingly erratic comments.
title: 'Republican voters remain overwhelmingly committed to Trump, whatever he may say or do'

description: In recent years, journalists and curious observers have discovered that individuals tasked with sensitive operations, particularly soldiers, have shared their physical activity on Strava, endangering their mission, their identity and even their safety.
title: Strava, the exercise app filled with security holes

description: 'StravaLeaks' (1/3). Three of the world's most important leaders have been put in danger due to their security guards' use of a sports social media app, Strava. The first part of our investigation looks into how the French president can be tracked thanks to his bodyguards' love of running.
title: How Emmanuel Macron can be tracked: Watch the first episode of StravaLeaks

description: American businessman Sean Combs, accused of multiple rapes, is the target of a federal investigation into potential sex trafficking. It was already against a backdrop of violence that the rapper and producer first appeared in Le Monde, on January 1, 1997.
title: Puff Daddy in Le Monde: From bling-bling media personality to inmate 37 452-054

description: Three months after Maduro's disputed re-election, a former oil minister was arrested, while the European Union awarded the Sakharov Prize to opponents Maria Corina Machado and Edmundo Gonzalez Urrutia.
title: In Venezuela, Nicolas Maduro drops new officials and tightens up his team

description: The president of the Federal Trade Commission, America's antitrust agency, is fighting the big monopolies. She irritates Republicans and is participating in the Biden administration's efforts to defend its actions against inflation.
title: Lina Khan, the woman making Big Tech tremble

description: As the gateway to Europe for the new cocaine routes, Montevideo, once known for its tranquillity, is now gripped by drug-related crime. This issue is at the heart of the campaign in Sunday's general elections.
title: Uruguay is gripped by cocaine trafficking amid elections

description: The vote is likely to replace the ruling conservatives with a center-left coalition, while leaving intact the NATO and EU member's strong support for Ukraine.
title: Lithuania votes in runoff election amid security concerns about Russia

description: China deployed fighter jets and drones around Taiwan on Sunday, Taipei said, after Beijing slammed the latest round of US arms sales to the island.
title: Taiwan says China held 'combat' patrol around island after latest US arms sales

description: The electoral commission announced on Sunday morning that Georgian Dream had won with 54% of the vote, despite protests from opposition parties. This will enable billionaire Bidzina Ivanishvili to form a government, but risks dashing the country's hopes of joining the European Union.
title: Georgia elections: Pro-Russian Georgian Dream holds onto power

description: Six consecutive votes have so far failed to yield a stable government, as the political turmoil has favored the country's far right.
title: Bulgaria votes in seventh election after three years of deadlock

description: New Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba and his Liberal Democratic Party, which has governed Japan for almost all of the past seven decades, are facing potentially their worst result since 2009.
title: Japan votes in tight election, with new PM Ishiba on shaky ground

description: The writer, a former soldier and ex-prisoner of the Russians, underlines the despair gripping Ukrainian fighters and warns of the difficulty of mobilizing new troops against Russia.
title: Stanislav Asseyev, Ukrainian journalist: 'We have a huge army of deserters roaming the country'

description: Falling sales of luxury watches, particularly in China, are forcing Swiss watchmakers to reduce working hours in their workshops.
title: Watchmakers in Switzerland cut back on working hours

description: The crisis facing European car manufacturers has more to do with their inability to produce a car that meets consumer needs than with the standards imposed by the EU, observed the philosopher and sociologist in her column.
title: Dominique Méda: 'A small, affordable and sustainable electric car can be made in France, a choice that would enable a just transition'
